====Usage notes====
Use (2) is discouraged in formal writing, because without that intonation a reader may expect use (1), which use (2) was originally an informal derivative of. That is, the reader may expect ''He is so good'' to be followed by an explanation or consequence of how good he is ‚Äì the underscore and exclamation mark are means of clarifying that use (2) is intended; capital ''SO'' is also used. Uses (2.1), (2.2), and (2.3) are themselves informal derivatives of uses (1) and (2), with the evaluation implied (e.g. "He is so good!" = "He is as good as some implied very good thing!"); they are pronounced with exaggerated intonation.

The difference between ''so'' and ''very'' in use (2) is that ''very'' is more descriptive or matter-of-fact, while ''so'' indicates more emotional involvement. This ''so'' is used by both men and women, but more frequently by women. For example, ''she is very pretty'' is a simple statement of fact; ''she is <u>so</u> pretty'' suggests admiration. Likewise, ''that is very typical'' is a simple statement; ''that is SO typical of him!'' is an indictment. A formal (and reserved) apology may be expressed ''I am very sorry'', but after elbowing someone in the nose during a basketball game, a man might say, ''Dude, I am <u>so</u> sorry!'' in order to ensure that it's understood as an accident.<ref>Mark Liberman, [http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=3866 "Ask Language Log: So feminine?"], 2012 March 26</ref>

